& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The fifth edition of the World Health Organization Classification system for breast tumors defines five distinct categories of papillary breast neoplasms characterized by papillary architecture composed of arborizing fibrovascular cores. The lesions span a wide spectrum of benign, atypical, and malignant neoplasms classified based on the nature of proliferating epithelial cells and the presence or absence of basal myoepithelial cells. The pathologic diagnosis of different papillary lesions on the basis of core needle biopsy can be challenging due to limited tissue sampling, artifacts, and overlapping morphologic features and immunohistochemical staining patterns. A distinction must be made between noninvasive and invasive forms of malignant papillary tumors because the prognostic staging and clinical management differ. A recent paradigm shift in management strategy favors a more conservative approach of surveillance rather than routine surgical excision for benign intraductal papillomas without atypia. The authors provide an overview of the various papillary lesions of the breast and their WHO classification. A description of the clinical, multimodality imaging, and histopathologic features is provided, along with an illustrative review of radiologic-pathologic correlation. Understanding the histologic and biologic spectrum of papillary lesions and radiologic-pathologic correlation is key for clinical management.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2025</div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/large/rg.240091.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240091">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240091">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Fibrovascular core architecture of breast papillary lesions. (A) Illustration of a fibrovascular core shows the dual–cell-layer lining with an outer epithelial cell layer and an inner myoepithelial cell (MEC) layer. The central core is composed of fibrous tissue and vasculature. (B) Photomicrograph shows intraductal papilloma with branching fibrovascular cores, with the double cell layer composed of the outer glandular epithelium (yellow arrow) and the inner basal myoepithelium (green arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×40.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig1.jpg" height="1438" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Fibrovascular core architecture of breast papillary lesions. <b>(A)</b> Illustration of a fibrovascular core shows the dual–cell-layer lining with an outer epithelial cell layer and an inner myoepithelial cell (MEC) layer. The central core is composed of fibrous tissue and vasculature. <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph shows intraductal papilloma with branching fibrovascular cores, with the double cell layer composed of the outer glandular epithelium (yellow arrow) and the inner basal myoepithelium (green arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows the locations of ducts and lobules in the breast and the typical distribution of the various papillary lesions. Lesions shown are a central solitary intraductal papilloma (black solid arrow), peripheral intraductal papillomas (black dashed arrow), papillary DCIS (white arrow), and papillary carcinoma (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig2.jpg" height="2570" width="2030" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustration shows the locations of ducts and lobules in the breast and the typical distribution of the various papillary lesions. Lesions shown are a central solitary intraductal papilloma (black solid arrow), peripheral intraductal papillomas (black dashed arrow), papillary DCIS (white arrow), and papillary carcinoma (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Photomicrographs of surgical specimens. (A) Photomicrograph of intraductal papilloma shows basal MECs in the papillary fronds (pink arrows) and the lesion periphery (green arrows). (Myosin immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×20.) (B) Photomicrograph of papillary DCIS shows that MECs are absent in the papillary fronds but present in the periphery of the lesion (pink arrows). (Myosin immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×60.) (C) Photomicrograph of IPC shows that basal MECs are absent in the papillary fronds (pink arrows) and at the lesion periphery (green arrows). Only the blood vessels show positive (brown) staining (yellow arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×60.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig3.jpg" height="3225" width="3199" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Photomicrographs of surgical specimens. <b>(A)</b> Photomicrograph of intraductal papilloma shows basal MECs in the papillary fronds (pink arrows) and the lesion periphery (green arrows). (Myosin immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph of papillary DCIS shows that MECs are absent in the papillary fronds but present in the periphery of the lesion (pink arrows). (Myosin immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×60.) <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of IPC shows that basal MECs are absent in the papillary fronds (pink arrows) and at the lesion periphery (green arrows). Only the blood vessels show positive (brown) staining (yellow arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×60.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows the presence or absence of MECs as highlighted with immunohistochemical staining in the papillae of fibrovascular cores and at the periphery of the lesion. The lesion architecture, the presence or absence of MECs, and the degree of cytologic atypia help to distinguish among the different categories of papillary lesions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig4.jpg" height="1892" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Illustration shows the presence or absence of MECs as highlighted with immunohistochemical staining in the papillae of fibrovascular cores and at the periphery of the lesion. The lesion architecture, the presence or absence of MECs, and the degree of cytologic atypia help to distinguish among the different categories of papillary lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagnostic imaging flow chart shows the workup for patients with pathologic nipple discharge based on the ACR appropriateness criteria guidelines."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig5.jpg" height="4077" width="3600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Diagnostic imaging flow chart shows the workup for patients with pathologic nipple discharge based on the ACR appropriateness criteria guidelines.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Intraductal papilloma diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy results in a 47-year-old woman with saline breast implants who presented with a palpable concern. (A) Craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an oval mass with circumscribed margins (arrow). (B) US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with microlobulated margins (arrow), with the implant posterior to the mass (*). (C) Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an oval circumscribed mass with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). (D) Photomicrograph of a biopsy specimen shows arborizing fibrovascular cores (yellow arrows) covered by MECs and overlying epithelial cells, and the same double layer of cells is found at the periphery. The epithelium shows a papilloma with usual ductal hyperplasia (green arrows), but an atypical pattern of ductal hyperplasia may also be seen in some cases. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig6.jpg" height="3592" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Intraductal papilloma diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy results in a 47-year-old woman with saline breast implants who presented with a palpable concern. <b>(A)</b> Craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an oval mass with circumscribed margins (arrow). <b>(B)</b> US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with microlobulated margins (arrow), with the implant posterior to the mass (*). <b>(C)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an oval circumscribed mass with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph of a biopsy specimen shows arborizing fibrovascular cores (yellow arrows) covered by MECs and overlying epithelial cells, and the same double layer of cells is found at the periphery. The epithelium shows a papilloma with usual ductal hyperplasia (green arrows), but an atypical pattern of ductal hyperplasia may also be seen in some cases. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="EPC in a 56-year-old man with a palpable concern. (A) Craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an oval high-density mass with circumscribed margins (arrow). (B) US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with circumscribed margins and internal frondlike solid components exhibiting characteristic “fingerlike” projections (arrows). (C) Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows the carcinoma cells in a cystic cavity, with a peripheral fibrous capsule (arrowheads) and prominent papillary architecture, with fibrovascular cores (arrows). Fingerlike projections on images correlate with arborizing fibrovascular cores at pathologic examination. Some of the papillary structures may undergo infarction and may be calcified over time or after percutaneous needle biopsy (circle). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig7.jpg" height="2813" width="2672" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. EPC in a 56-year-old man with a palpable concern. <b>(A)</b> Craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an oval high-density mass with circumscribed margins (arrow). <b>(B)</b> US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with circumscribed margins and internal frondlike solid components exhibiting characteristic “fingerlike” projections (arrows). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows the carcinoma cells in a cystic cavity, with a peripheral fibrous capsule (arrowheads) and prominent papillary architecture, with fibrovascular cores (arrows). Fingerlike projections on images correlate with arborizing fibrovascular cores at pathologic examination. Some of the papillary structures may undergo infarction and may be calcified over time or after percutaneous needle biopsy (circle). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Intraductal papilloma diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy in a 44-year-old man with bloody nipple discharge of the left breast and mammographic and US findings negative for abnormality. Contrast-enhanced MRI was performed due to persistent symptoms. (A) Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows an intraductal oval circumscribed mass with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). (B) Axial color map MR image shows the mass with washout delayed kinetics (arrow) and a dilated proximal duct (arrowhead). Plateau or washout delayed-enhancement kinetics are typical findings of a papilloma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig8.jpg" height="1131" width="4000" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Intraductal papilloma diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy in a 44-year-old man with bloody nipple discharge of the left breast and mammographic and US findings negative for abnormality. Contrast-enhanced MRI was performed due to persistent symptoms. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows an intraductal oval circumscribed mass with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Axial color map MR image shows the mass with washout delayed kinetics (arrow) and a dilated proximal duct (arrowhead). Plateau or washout delayed-enhancement kinetics are typical findings of a papilloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Sclerosing papilloma diagnosed at core needle biopsy in a 40-year-old woman with a mass detected at high-risk screening contrast-enhanced MRI. (A) Axial postcontrast MR image shows an oval mass with irregular margins in the left breast, with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). (B) Axial color map MR image shows the mass with washout delayed kinetics (arrow). (C) US image shows an oval mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). The mass was occult at mammography (not shown). (D) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows thickened and sclerotic papillae and papillary fronds (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig9.jpg" height="1319" width="2000" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Sclerosing papilloma diagnosed at core needle biopsy in a 40-year-old woman with a mass detected at high-risk screening contrast-enhanced MRI. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast MR image shows an oval mass with irregular margins in the left breast, with a homogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Axial color map MR image shows the mass with washout delayed kinetics (arrow). <b>(C)</b> US image shows an oval mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). The mass was occult at mammography (not shown). <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows thickened and sclerotic papillae and papillary fronds (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Juvenile papillomatosis in a 25-year-old woman with bilateral clear nipple discharge. (A) US image of the right breast shows multiple intraductal oval and round hypoechoic masses (arrows) in a segmental distribution. (B) Axial postcontrast subtraction MR image shows innumerable bilateral intraductal enhancing masses in a segmental distribution in all four quadrants, correlating with the US findings. (C) Photomicrograph of mastectomy specimen shows multiple papillae (arrows) fused together by usual ductal hyperplasia (arrowheads). This structure was within a larger cyst that is beyond the margins. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) (D) Photomicrograph of mastectomy specimen shows a large cyst occupied by papillomas and surrounded by smaller cysts with apocrine metaplasia (apo) and usual ductal hyperplasia (udh). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig10.jpg" height="1444" width="2000" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Juvenile papillomatosis in a 25-year-old woman with bilateral clear nipple discharge. <b>(A)</b> US image of the right breast shows multiple intraductal oval and round hypoechoic masses (arrows) in a segmental distribution. <b>(B)</b> Axial postcontrast subtraction MR image shows innumerable bilateral intraductal enhancing masses in a segmental distribution in all four quadrants, correlating with the US findings. <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of mastectomy specimen shows multiple papillae (arrows) fused together by usual ductal hyperplasia (arrowheads). This structure was within a larger cyst that is beyond the margins. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph of mastectomy specimen shows a large cyst occupied by papillomas and surrounded by smaller cysts with apocrine metaplasia <i>(apo)</i> and usual ductal hyperplasia <i>(udh)</i>. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Characteristic gross and histologic features of juvenile papillomatosis. (A) Photograph shows multiple cystic structures in a dense fibrous stroma resembling Swiss cheese. (B) Photomicrograph shows microscopic features including florid intraductal epithelial hyperplasia intermixed with cysts of varying sizes or dilated ducts and the presence of benign papillomas. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig11.jpg" height="612" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Characteristic gross and histologic features of juvenile papillomatosis. <b>(A)</b> Photograph shows multiple cystic structures in a dense fibrous stroma resembling Swiss cheese. <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph shows microscopic features including florid intraductal epithelial hyperplasia intermixed with cysts of varying sizes or dilated ducts and the presence of benign papillomas. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Intraductal papilloma with ADH diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy results in a 69-year-old woman with a palpable concern. (A) Craniocaudal mammogram of the left breast at the area of palpable concern suggests a superficial oval fat-containing mass (arrow). (B) Targeted US image at the area of the palpable concern shows a superficial oval mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). (C) Photomicrograph of core needle biopsy specimen shows fragments of a papillary lesion (arrows), with associated severe ADH bordering on low-grade DCIS. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×4.) (D) Photomicrograph at higher magnification shows proliferation of epithelial cells with low-grade atypia and papillary fronds. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig12.jpg" height="1230" width="2073" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Intraductal papilloma with ADH diagnosed on the basis of core needle biopsy results in a 69-year-old woman with a palpable concern. <b>(A)</b> Craniocaudal mammogram of the left breast at the area of palpable concern suggests a superficial oval fat-containing mass (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Targeted US image at the area of the palpable concern shows a superficial oval mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of core needle biopsy specimen shows fragments of a papillary lesion (arrows), with associated severe ADH bordering on low-grade DCIS. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph at higher magnification shows proliferation of epithelial cells with low-grade atypia and papillary fronds. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Papilloma with DCIS in a 69-year-old woman with a palpable concern. (A) Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the left breast shows an irregular mass with an indistinct margin associated with pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). (B) US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with a microlobulated margin containing echogenic foci (arrow). (C) Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows DCIS (green arrows) surrounding an intraductal papilloma. Thick fibrovascular cores (yellow arrows) show the overlying neoplastic epithelium. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig13.jpg" height="1280" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Papilloma with DCIS in a 69-year-old woman with a palpable concern. <b>(A)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the left breast shows an irregular mass with an indistinct margin associated with pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). <b>(B)</b> US image shows an oval complex cystic and solid mass with a microlobulated margin containing echogenic foci (arrow). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows DCIS (green arrows) surrounding an intraductal papilloma. Thick fibrovascular cores (yellow arrows) show the overlying neoplastic epithelium. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Papillary DCIS in an 80-year-old woman who was recalled from screening mammography for an area of focal asymmetry. (A) Spot compression tomosynthesis craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast demonstrates multiple irregular masses and focal asymmetry in a segmental distribution (arrows). (B) US image shows multiple irregular intraductal hypoechoic masses (arrows). (C) Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows corresponding segmental distribution nonmass enhancement (arrows). Core needle biopsy results revealed extensive DCIS with mucin and a papillary, solid papillary, and cribriform growth pattern, focally involving an underlying papilloma. (D) Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows DCIS with papillary architecture. Fibrovascular cores are seen between proliferative neoplastic cells (yellow arrows). These fibrovascular cores are typically thin and delicate as compared with the broad ones observed in intraductal papillomas. There is adjacent cribriform-pattern DCIS (green arrow). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig14.jpg" height="1735" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Papillary DCIS in an 80-year-old woman who was recalled from screening mammography for an area of focal asymmetry. <b>(A)</b> Spot compression tomosynthesis craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast demonstrates multiple irregular masses and focal asymmetry in a segmental distribution (arrows). <b>(B)</b> US image shows multiple irregular intraductal hypoechoic masses (arrows). <b>(C)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows corresponding segmental distribution nonmass enhancement (arrows). Core needle biopsy results revealed extensive DCIS with mucin and a papillary, solid papillary, and cribriform growth pattern, focally involving an underlying papilloma. <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows DCIS with papillary architecture. Fibrovascular cores are seen between proliferative neoplastic cells (yellow arrows). These fibrovascular cores are typically thin and delicate as compared with the broad ones observed in intraductal papillomas. There is adjacent cribriform-pattern DCIS (green arrow). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="EPC with invasion in a 68-year-old woman. (A) Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows invasive carcinoma of no special type (invasive ductal carcinoma) (yellow arrow) arising in association with an EPC. The EPC has neoplastic papillary proliferation with branching fibrovascular cores and is surrounded by a thick fibrous capsule (green arrows). The invasive carcinoma component is seen extending beyond the fibrous capsule into the surrounding stroma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×2.) (B) Photomicrograph shows neoplastic cells with low-grade atypia and a well-circumscribed pushing border (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.) (C) Photomicrograph at a higher magnification shows tumor cells (grade 1 of 3) (yellow arrows), with infiltrative tubular and cribriform glands in a desmoplastic stroma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig15.jpg" height="1053" width="1850" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. EPC with invasion in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(A)</b> Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows invasive carcinoma of no special type (invasive ductal carcinoma) (yellow arrow) arising in association with an EPC. The EPC has neoplastic papillary proliferation with branching fibrovascular cores and is surrounded by a thick fibrous capsule (green arrows). The invasive carcinoma component is seen extending beyond the fibrous capsule into the surrounding stroma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×2.) <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph shows neoplastic cells with low-grade atypia and a well-circumscribed pushing border (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph at a higher magnification shows tumor cells (grade 1 of 3) (yellow arrows), with infiltrative tubular and cribriform glands in a desmoplastic stroma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="SPC in situ in a 74-year-old woman with known biopsy-proven invasive lobular carcinoma in the left breast. She underwent MRI to evaluate the extent of disease, and a suspicious mass was found in the right breast. (A) Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an irregular mass with an irregular margin and a heterogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). (B) US image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). US-guided biopsy showed SPC in situ. The mass was mammographically occult (not shown). (C) Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows SPC in situ, which is characterized by multiple circumscribed nodules of monotonous epithelial cells (arrows). Discrete papillae are not readily apparent due to cellular proliferation in a solid pattern. There are changes associated with a prior biopsy (*) and occasional microcystic spaces (arrowhead). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) (D) Photomicrograph at a higher power shows proliferative cells palisading around delicate fibrovascular cores (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig16.jpg" height="1251" width="1850" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. SPC in situ in a 74-year-old woman with known biopsy-proven invasive lobular carcinoma in the left breast. She underwent MRI to evaluate the extent of disease, and a suspicious mass was found in the right breast. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an irregular mass with an irregular margin and a heterogeneous internal enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(B)</b> US image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with a microlobulated margin (arrow). US-guided biopsy showed SPC in situ. The mass was mammographically occult (not shown). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of a surgical specimen shows SPC in situ, which is characterized by multiple circumscribed nodules of monotonous epithelial cells (arrows). Discrete papillae are not readily apparent due to cellular proliferation in a solid pattern. There are changes associated with a prior biopsy (*) and occasional microcystic spaces (arrowhead). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph at a higher power shows proliferative cells palisading around delicate fibrovascular cores (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="IPC in a 76-year-old woman with a screening-detected right breast mass. (A) Spot compression craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an irregular mass with spiculated margins (arrow). (B) US image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with an angular margin (arrow). (C) Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows papillary carcinoma with irregular infiltrative borders (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.) (D) Photomicrograph at a higher magnification shows destructive invasion of the periductal stroma by carcinoma. The carcinoma shows thin and delicate fibrovascular cores, creating a papillary architecture (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig17.jpg" height="1274" width="2239" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. IPC in a 76-year-old woman with a screening-detected right breast mass. <b>(A)</b> Spot compression craniocaudal mammogram of the right breast shows an irregular mass with spiculated margins (arrow). <b>(B)</b> US image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with an angular margin (arrow). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows papillary carcinoma with irregular infiltrative borders (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×10.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph at a higher magnification shows destructive invasion of the periductal stroma by carcinoma. The carcinoma shows thin and delicate fibrovascular cores, creating a papillary architecture (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Invasive micropapillary carcinoma in a 75-year-old man. High-powered photomicrograph shows nests of tumor cells, some with hollow central spaces. Although this tumor exhibits a papillary growth pattern, it lacks central fibrovascular cores. This separate entity is thus distinguished from IPC histologically. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240091/asset/images/rg.240091.fig18.jpg" height="790" width="1015" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Invasive micropapillary carcinoma in a 75-year-old man. High-powered photomicrograph shows nests of tumor cells, some with hollow central spaces. Although this tumor exhibits a papillary growth pattern, it lacks central fibrovascular cores. This separate entity is thus distinguished from IPC histologically. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240091&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has=